**Problem:** `acquire()` at `lock.py:57-72` has a classic TOCTOU race — between reading the lock file PID and writing our own, a concurrent process can read the same stale state, both believing they hold the lock.

**Solution:** Replace check-then-write with `fcntl.flock(fd, LOCK_EX | LOCK_NB)` — kernel-enforced exclusive lock, atomic and auto-released on process exit. Track fds per-project in `self._fds: dict[str, int]` for multi-project lock support.

**Fallback:** On platforms without `fcntl` (Windows), keep existing PID-based logic unchanged.

